WEBVTT

00:00.701 --> 00:02.167
             [♪♪♪]

00:08.609 --> 00:10.609
        [DOORBELL RINGS]

00:19.053 --> 00:20.552
 Good morning,
 Major Healey.

00:20.554 --> 00:21.987
             Hi, Jeannie.
          Uh, where's Tony?

00:21.989 --> 00:23.088
                He asked me
              to pick him up.

00:23.090 --> 00:24.356
    Oh, he overslept.

00:24.358 --> 00:26.525
Would you like a cup of coffee
while you're waiting?

00:26.527 --> 00:27.526
                     No,
             I'm in a hurry. I--

00:27.528 --> 00:28.593
         Why?

00:28.595 --> 00:30.162
                Well, Friday is
              General Peterson's

00:30.164 --> 00:31.530
              10th anniversary
                as a general,

00:31.532 --> 00:33.732
      and, uh, well, Dr. Bellows
      wants to put on this show.

00:33.734 --> 00:35.501
     And I have to find somebody
            to take charge

00:35.503 --> 00:36.968
            of the entertainment
                 committee.

00:36.970 --> 00:39.438
Oh, Major Nelson is very good
at being in charge of things.

00:39.440 --> 00:40.805
                 Well, it's not
               a matter of that.

00:40.807 --> 00:42.908
         You gotta know somebody
        that's in show business.

00:42.910 --> 00:44.743
         You gotta have somebody
           that has a big act.

00:44.745 --> 00:46.811
         He doesn't know anybody
        in show business at all.

00:46.813 --> 00:48.446
      I will help him.

00:48.448 --> 00:50.114
              Well, you co-- No.
                Oh, no. Oh, no.

00:50.116 --> 00:52.016
He doesn't like you helping him.
          Don't do it.

00:52.018 --> 00:54.018
How would it look
if some other master's genie

00:54.020 --> 00:55.053
was in charge?

00:56.123 --> 00:57.255
                    Yeah, I see
                  what you mean.

00:57.257 --> 00:58.924
                   No! No, no.
                 Oh, no. Oh, no.

00:58.926 --> 01:00.992
He would enjoy himself.
            Forget-- Not me. No.

01:00.994 --> 01:03.294
He may not think so, but he
would enjoy himself a great--

01:03.296 --> 01:04.495
                    That's out.
     Major Healey,

01:04.498 --> 01:07.031
   if Major Nelson is not
       put in charge,

01:07.033 --> 01:08.734
     I can promise you
     that on the night

01:08.736 --> 01:10.268
of General Peterson's party,

01:10.270 --> 01:13.338
       there will be
   a terrible hurricane.

01:13.340 --> 01:15.039
             [♪♪♪]

01:15.041 --> 01:16.040
         The night of the party?

01:17.378 --> 01:19.044
       And a tidal wave.

01:19.046 --> 01:21.246
       General Peterson's party?

01:22.416 --> 01:23.881
         And a typhoon.

01:23.883 --> 01:26.884
 And we'll all be sitting around
        having cocktails?

01:28.021 --> 01:30.956
              Hm. Well, I guess
            that's it. Ha-ha-ha.

01:30.958 --> 01:32.957
   I guess we found the new head
         of our committee.

01:32.959 --> 01:34.893
          [LAUGHS]

01:36.329 --> 01:38.397
       Oh. And, shh,
not a word to Major Nelson.

01:38.399 --> 01:39.664
               Yeah, not a word.
                      Shh.

01:39.666 --> 01:40.766
               Yeah, not a word.
                    Oh, boy.

01:40.768 --> 01:41.900
                 Guess I'll be--

01:41.902 --> 01:45.337
Oh, hi, Roge.
I'm sorry. I overslept.

01:45.339 --> 01:46.338
     Do you know something?

01:46.340 --> 01:47.339
                      Huh, what?

01:47.341 --> 01:48.607
      You should've stayed
            in bed.

01:55.249 --> 01:57.249
             [♪♪♪]

02:43.797 --> 02:46.264
             [♪♪♪]

02:51.071 --> 02:53.304
             [♪♪♪]

03:21.201 --> 03:22.534
          Frankly, Major Healey,

03:22.536 --> 03:24.736
      I would never have thought
       of Major Nelson for this.

03:24.738 --> 03:26.404
    Ah, well, frankly,
   neither did I, sir.

03:26.406 --> 03:27.906
   It just came to me
    out of the blue.

03:27.908 --> 03:30.408
  Do you think he can get a top
 entertainer for Friday evening?

03:30.410 --> 03:32.277
   Well, if he can't,
he knows someone who can.

03:32.279 --> 03:34.880
Uh, he's really quite anxious
to head the committee, though.

03:34.882 --> 03:36.982
      Oh, strange. He never said
        a word to me about it.

03:36.984 --> 03:38.516
    Well, you know
  how modest Tony is.

03:38.518 --> 03:40.118
    But he'll come up
   with someone great.

03:40.120 --> 03:42.087
               Ah, Major Nelson.
  Yes.

03:42.089 --> 03:43.789
          I just want to express
             my appreciation.

03:43.791 --> 03:45.256
Your appreciation, sir?

03:45.258 --> 03:47.859
For volunteering to take charge
  of General Peterson's party.

03:47.861 --> 03:49.561
     I haven't had a chance
       to tell you that--

03:49.563 --> 03:51.029
For volunteering
to take--?

03:51.031 --> 03:53.598
      Uh, Major Healey told me
   how anxious you are to do it.

03:53.600 --> 03:56.367
Oh, Major Healey
told you that,
did he? Thanks.

03:56.369 --> 03:57.969
       We were considering using

03:57.971 --> 03:59.705
   some of the amateur talent
          around here,

03:59.707 --> 04:01.807
but with all the people
in show business you know,

04:01.809 --> 04:03.274
that won't be necessary,
        will it?

04:03.276 --> 04:04.509
          People in show
           business I--

04:04.511 --> 04:06.211
                I told you he's
               modest. Ha-ha-ha.

04:06.213 --> 04:08.479
I don't know one single person
in the entertainment--

04:08.481 --> 04:10.281
             That's right.
       Most of them are married.

04:10.283 --> 04:13.418
 Well, it's in your hands now,
         Major Nelson.

04:13.420 --> 04:15.420
This is one of the most
important evenings

04:15.422 --> 04:17.389
  in General Peterson's life.

04:17.391 --> 04:19.123
Oh, and, uh,

04:19.125 --> 04:22.093
     may I just say one thing?
   Yes, sir.

04:22.095 --> 04:24.362
        Don't let me down.

04:24.364 --> 04:25.897
             [♪♪♪]

04:25.899 --> 04:26.931
   Yes, sir.

04:26.933 --> 04:28.032
             [♪♪♪]

04:32.205 --> 04:33.739
           Why?

04:33.741 --> 04:36.307
   Well, if you're not the head
  of the entertainment committee

04:36.309 --> 04:38.577
during General Peterson's party,
      there's going to be

04:38.579 --> 04:42.113
       a hurricane, a tidal wave
             and a typhoon.

04:42.115 --> 04:43.382
       Jeannie.
   Jeannie did that?

04:43.384 --> 04:44.383
               Not so loud.
                   Shh.

04:44.385 --> 04:45.384
                     Don't get
                   her mad, now.

04:45.386 --> 04:47.051
Wh-why would she
make you do that? Why?

04:47.053 --> 04:49.454
 How would it look if some other
   genie's master got the job?

04:49.456 --> 04:51.656
      I mean, all you have to do
     is get a great entertainer.

04:51.658 --> 04:52.957
        Oh, sure.
   I don't know anybody

04:52.959 --> 04:54.760
in the entertainment field.
       I just told--

04:54.762 --> 04:55.960
         Yeah, but Jeannie does.

04:55.962 --> 04:57.929
Yeah, I'm sure she does.
I can just see her now.

04:57.931 --> 04:59.598
Uh, uh, Shakespeare
will come out

04:59.600 --> 05:01.065
and introduce
Sarah Bernhardt,

05:01.067 --> 05:03.034
and then Ben Hur will do
a little chariot race.

05:03.036 --> 05:04.202
               Yeah, yeah.
              Wait a minute.

05:04.204 --> 05:06.671
            Then after Ben Hur,
          maybe some gladiators.

05:06.673 --> 05:08.273
              Wait a minute,
         you have the first act.

05:08.275 --> 05:09.675
                    Oh.
    You got the whole first act.

05:09.677 --> 05:10.942
             Now,
     I can't be the head

05:10.944 --> 05:12.410
     of the entertainment
          committee.

05:12.412 --> 05:14.145
            Why not?
Yeah, why not?

05:14.147 --> 05:16.347
I bet Jeannie knows a lot
of people in show business.

05:16.349 --> 05:17.348
                       Oh, yeah.
             Of course.

05:17.350 --> 05:18.616
           I know hundreds,
              thousands.

05:18.618 --> 05:19.884
                       Yeah?
Didn't I tell you?

05:19.886 --> 05:22.119
       What is show business?

05:22.121 --> 05:25.022
  Jeannie, you-- You volunteered
     me for-- For-- For this.

05:25.024 --> 05:26.591
                 What do I do
              for entertainment?

05:26.593 --> 05:27.592
             Oh, that.

05:27.594 --> 05:28.593
         [ALL LAUGHING]

05:28.595 --> 05:29.861
                     Yeah, that.

05:29.863 --> 05:32.396
     Well, we could start
with a chariot race by Ben Hur

05:32.398 --> 05:33.498
     and then some gladiators.

05:33.500 --> 05:35.199
Well, I guess I better be
running along.

05:35.201 --> 05:37.769
   Yeah, yeah. A fine friend you
    turned out to be. I really--

05:40.273 --> 05:42.607
   Are you very angry,
         master?

05:46.245 --> 05:48.245
             Why did you
            do this to me?

05:48.247 --> 05:50.381
  Well, I-- I thought
    you might like

05:50.383 --> 05:52.617
 to do something nice
 for General Peterson.

05:52.619 --> 05:53.985
               Oh, I would.
                 I would.

05:53.987 --> 05:56.153
       But I don't know anything
          about entertainment.

05:56.155 --> 05:57.154
Oh, well, I can get you

05:57.156 --> 05:58.890
Cleopatra's dancing girls.
                   Huh?

05:58.892 --> 05:59.891
 They are the most--

05:59.893 --> 06:01.626
              No, no, no, no,
                no, no, no.

06:01.628 --> 06:02.827
     I would like
    to help you--

06:02.829 --> 06:04.996
             Believe me,
     you've done enough. Really.

06:04.998 --> 06:07.799
Well, what will you do?

06:07.801 --> 06:09.066
              I'll go to Miami.

06:09.068 --> 06:10.434
You're going to run away?

06:10.436 --> 06:12.737
                    No.
           I'm gonna go to Miami

06:12.739 --> 06:15.006
      because a lot of big stars
          work down in Miami

06:15.008 --> 06:16.508
       in hotels and nightclubs.

06:16.510 --> 06:19.076
Maybe I can persuade one of them
to come up to the space center.

06:19.078 --> 06:20.879
Oh, you are brilliant,
       master.

06:20.881 --> 06:21.880
                 [WHISTLES]

06:21.882 --> 06:23.147
                Here we are.

06:23.149 --> 06:24.415
Do you see anyone you know?

06:24.417 --> 06:25.550
                      No.

06:25.552 --> 06:27.752
       But I see somebody
       I'd like to have.

06:27.754 --> 06:29.453
           Ah, he'd never do it.

06:29.455 --> 06:30.755
Who would never do it?

06:30.757 --> 06:32.724
One of the greatest entertainers
         in the world.

06:32.726 --> 06:33.758
            Sammy Davis Jr.

06:33.760 --> 06:37.528
Oh. Is he better
than Ben Hur?

06:37.530 --> 06:39.564
             [♪♪♪]

06:41.001 --> 06:43.101
             Sammy Davis Jr.?

06:43.103 --> 06:44.669
            Do you think you can
               really get him?

06:44.671 --> 06:45.937
Well, I don't know, Roge.

06:45.939 --> 06:48.139
Um, he-- He's doing a show
in a hotel in Miami.

06:48.141 --> 06:50.441
I'm going down there tonight
to see if I can talk to him.

06:50.443 --> 06:51.776
                  Oh, you gonna
                  take Jeannie?

06:51.778 --> 06:53.044
       [LAUGHING]
    Are you kidding?

06:53.046 --> 06:54.613
         She'll never let you go
               without her.

06:54.615 --> 06:55.981
     She's not gonna
     know about it.

06:55.983 --> 06:57.315
               How are you gonna
                  manage that?

06:57.317 --> 06:59.651
Well, don't worry about it.
I'll think of something.

06:59.653 --> 07:01.419
There's Dr. Bellows.
I'll see you later.

07:01.421 --> 07:02.654
                       Okay.
                     Good luck.

07:02.656 --> 07:04.923
BELLOWS:
Oh, uh, here are
some research books.

07:04.925 --> 07:07.025
The new auditory charts.

07:07.027 --> 07:09.427
I thought you and Major Nelson
might like to look them over

07:09.429 --> 07:10.529
before the test tomorrow.

07:10.531 --> 07:12.296
   Well, I better look them over
            myself, sir.

07:12.298 --> 07:13.798
               I don't think
          he's going to be back.

07:13.800 --> 07:15.099
                 You see,
          he went down to Miami.

07:15.101 --> 07:16.100
 May I ask why?

07:16.102 --> 07:17.702
            Well, he went to get
               Sammy Davis Jr.

07:17.704 --> 07:19.404
   for General Peterson's party.

07:19.406 --> 07:22.206
Sammy Davis Jr.?

07:22.208 --> 07:25.544
You mean...he's agreed
to entertain for the general?

07:25.546 --> 07:27.145
         Well, sir, I didn't say
              that-- That--

07:27.147 --> 07:28.880
Oh, that's marvelous.

07:28.882 --> 07:30.281
I happen to know that he's

07:30.283 --> 07:32.083
General Peterson's
favorite performer.

07:32.085 --> 07:33.151
                Well, it's not
                  all set--

07:33.153 --> 07:34.786
    Wait until
I tell the general.

07:34.788 --> 07:35.854
               Oh, I wouldn't--

07:35.856 --> 07:37.321
Oh, he's going to be
very pleased.

07:37.323 --> 07:39.357
      Oh, uh,
about those charts.

07:39.359 --> 07:40.358
Look them over.
                    Yeah.

07:40.360 --> 07:41.660
And, uh, here.
                    Sir?

07:41.662 --> 07:43.895
Oh, uh-- Sammy Davis Jr.!
                   Sir.

07:43.897 --> 07:45.830
          Wait. Wait. Sir.

07:53.473 --> 07:56.942
    Me and my big mouth!

07:56.944 --> 07:58.577
             [♪♪♪]

08:13.126 --> 08:15.093
               Oh, are you ready
                for bed, master?
 Oh, yeah--

08:15.095 --> 08:16.928
                 It is so early.
    Oh, e-early?

08:16.930 --> 08:18.262
      Oh, no,
    it's 10:00.

08:18.264 --> 08:20.164
                   Ten o'clock?
         Yeah.

08:20.166 --> 08:22.400
                 Why, I thought
               it was only 8:00.

08:22.402 --> 08:24.803
      My hourglass must be slow.
         Mm-hm.

08:24.805 --> 08:26.237
      [LAUGHING]
   Yeah, probably.

08:26.239 --> 08:28.039
     Well, I've had
a pretty hard day. I'm--

08:28.041 --> 08:30.208
I'm gonna get to bed.
You better get to bed too.

08:30.210 --> 08:31.810
       Good night.

08:31.812 --> 08:32.811
                     [YAWNS]

08:32.813 --> 08:34.078
    Good night, master.

08:34.081 --> 08:35.714
                     Good night.

08:35.716 --> 08:37.715
             [♪♪♪]

08:42.321 --> 08:43.453
                       Hello.

08:43.456 --> 08:44.856
           Heh. Good night.

08:44.858 --> 08:46.991
    Good night, master.

08:46.993 --> 08:48.693
                 [YAWNS]

09:04.878 --> 09:08.145
             [♪♪♪]

09:11.551 --> 09:14.352
  All right, testing, testing.
        One, two, three.

09:14.354 --> 09:15.520
          Ah, there it goes.

09:15.522 --> 09:17.288
           Now, guys, if we can
          take it one more time,

09:17.290 --> 09:18.656
       I got the tape recorder--
  Sam.

09:18.658 --> 09:20.358
We've been rehearsing
for three hours.

09:20.360 --> 09:22.727
I know you're the boss,
but you're gonna kill yourself.

09:22.729 --> 09:24.963
George, if I gotta go, will you
   let it be in the key of G.

09:24.965 --> 09:26.631
           Okay? Let's sing.
     Sammy, he's right.

09:26.633 --> 09:29.034
If you don't rest, you're gonna
have a nervous breakdown.

09:29.036 --> 09:31.335
      "Nervous breakdown."
That's all I ever hear from you.

09:31.337 --> 09:33.004
            Do me a favor
     and take care of the money.

09:33.006 --> 09:34.606
              Let me take care
            of the arrangements.

09:34.608 --> 09:36.074
            Come on, once again,
                huh, George?

09:36.076 --> 09:37.775
            Nice and light, now.
[DOORBELL RINGS]

09:37.777 --> 09:40.078
                   [SCATTING]

09:40.080 --> 09:42.513
[PLAYING SOFT
JAZZ MUSIC]

09:42.515 --> 09:43.882
               Yeah.
          Can I help you?

09:43.884 --> 09:46.117
     Uh, yeah, I'd like to speak
        to Mr. Davis, please.

09:46.119 --> 09:48.186
         Sure.
      One moment.

09:48.188 --> 09:49.988
    ♪ The girl from Ipanema
         Goes walking ♪

09:49.990 --> 09:52.390
     ♪ And when she passes
     Each time she passes ♪

09:52.392 --> 09:53.692
             ♪ I go-- ♪

09:53.694 --> 09:54.993
         Now, oh, oh, oh.

09:54.995 --> 09:56.594
Can I help you?
        It's not happening.

09:56.596 --> 09:58.596
Oh, yes, I'd like to speak
to Mr. Davis.

09:58.598 --> 10:00.231
                 No, I'm sorry.
                He's rehearsing.

10:00.233 --> 10:02.366
       Perhaps I could help you.
            I'm his manager.

10:02.368 --> 10:03.768
        Oh, yes,
     certainly, um--

10:03.770 --> 10:06.270
Well, I'd like to speak to him
about the possibility of doing

10:06.272 --> 10:07.906
     a performance
 at, uh, Cape Kennedy.

10:07.908 --> 10:11.175
General Peterson is celebrating
his 10th year as a general.

10:11.177 --> 10:12.544
 Oh, Sammy loves
 to do benefits.

10:12.546 --> 10:13.912
Oh, good, good.
That's good.

10:13.914 --> 10:15.479
But this is not exactly
a benefit.

10:15.481 --> 10:17.983
It more or less falls under
the heading of "saving my life."

10:17.985 --> 10:19.284
               What night is it?

10:19.286 --> 10:21.752
Oh, it's, uh, Friday night.
     Uh, Friday night.

10:21.754 --> 10:23.054
    I could send a car
      down for him.

10:23.056 --> 10:24.755
            Oh, I'm afraid Sammy
              couldn't get away.

10:24.757 --> 10:26.357
               He does two shows
                 a night here.

10:26.359 --> 10:28.226
Oh, well. Then maybe
I could send a jet.

10:28.228 --> 10:29.527
   Mister. Mister--

10:29.529 --> 10:31.296
          Well, unless you could
               postpone it.

10:31.298 --> 10:32.797
  Uh, until when?

10:32.799 --> 10:36.735
  Well, let's see. Sammy's first
    free day is, uh, May 15th.

10:36.737 --> 10:37.769
      May 15th?

10:37.771 --> 10:39.003
           A year from May 15th.

10:39.005 --> 10:40.405
              He's booked solid.

10:40.407 --> 10:41.672
   Oh, I see.
       SAMMY: Oh, oh, oh.

10:41.674 --> 10:42.974
    Well, thank you.

10:42.976 --> 10:43.975
 It was worth a try.

10:43.977 --> 10:45.509
                  I'm sorry.
          Yeah.

10:45.511 --> 10:47.345
               Well, who shall I
                tell him called?

10:47.347 --> 10:49.814
Oh, uh, the late
Major Anthony Nelson.

10:49.816 --> 10:51.816
       [LAUGHS]

10:57.490 --> 10:58.489
             SAMMY:
           One time.

10:58.491 --> 10:59.524
               Here we go.

10:59.526 --> 11:01.992
          One, two, three, four.

11:01.994 --> 11:04.529
         [BAND PLAYING
        SOFT JAZZ MUSIC]

11:04.531 --> 11:06.764
               ♪ Tall and tan
          And young and lovely ♪

11:06.766 --> 11:09.066
        ♪ The girl from Ipanema
             Goes walking ♪

11:09.068 --> 11:11.702
          ♪ And when she passes
          Each time she passes ♪

11:11.704 --> 11:14.138
             ♪ I go, "Ahhh" ♪

11:14.140 --> 11:16.373
              ♪ When she walks
           It's like the samba ♪

11:16.375 --> 11:19.143
           ♪ That sways so cool
          And swings so gentle ♪

11:19.145 --> 11:22.012
          ♪ That when she passes
          Each time she passes ♪

11:22.014 --> 11:25.450
             ♪ I go, "Ahhh" ♪

11:25.452 --> 11:28.820
   ♪ But I watch her so gladly ♪

11:28.822 --> 11:34.391
   ♪ H-h-h-how can I tell her
         I love her? ♪

11:34.393 --> 11:38.262
      ♪ Gee, I would give
       My heart gladly ♪

11:38.264 --> 11:41.131
   ♪ But each day when she walks
            To the sea ♪

11:41.133 --> 11:43.835
    ♪ She looks straight ahead
           Not at me ♪

11:43.837 --> 11:46.203
            ♪ Tall and tan
        And young and lovely ♪

11:46.205 --> 11:48.506
         ♪ The girl from Ipanema
              Goes walking ♪

11:48.508 --> 11:52.777
   ♪ And when she passes I smile
       But she doesn't see ♪

11:52.779 --> 11:53.878
  ♪ She ain't looking at me ♪

11:53.880 --> 11:55.279
           [SCATTING]

11:55.281 --> 11:56.647
  ♪ She ain't looking at me ♪

11:56.649 --> 11:57.748
             [SCATS]

11:57.750 --> 12:00.250
  ♪ She ain't looking at me ♪

12:00.252 --> 12:03.454
          ♪ It's not me
     That she will ever see ♪

12:03.456 --> 12:05.022
              ♪ Ah ♪

12:05.024 --> 12:07.157
  Well, it ain't the Monkees,
     but it'll have to do.

12:07.159 --> 12:09.059
          Hey, John and Michael,

12:09.061 --> 12:11.061
         why don't you go get
     some coffee in the kitchen.

12:11.063 --> 12:12.730
     I know it took a long time,
             but you see?

12:12.732 --> 12:14.164
         Practice makes perfect.

12:14.166 --> 12:15.700
Okay, Sam.

12:15.702 --> 12:17.067
Oh, look, Sam.
                  Yeah?

12:17.069 --> 12:19.470
You will try to get a little
sleep before the show tonight?

12:19.472 --> 12:21.472
          Sure, I'll take a nap.
